Comparative Value at Risk analysis in GARCH models

Introduction

The aim is to compare the risk in the cryptocurrency market, the tests include the estimation of the conditional variance function in the GARCH family models. Performed tests in accordance with the selected products: Ardor, Waves, RavenCoin and Zcash. Three GARCH class models - "GARCH" and its extensions - EGARCH and CGARCH, were estimated. Data sample was scraped from the Coingecko website LINK. 

library(rvest)

1. Data preparation and analysis

Data was obtained using web-scraping. They come from the CoinGecko website. For each cryptocurrency, its closing price and capitalization were kept and combined into one data table.

zcash = getdata('zcash', start_date='2018-05-03', end_date='2021-06-11')
waves = getdata('waves', start_date='2018-05-03', end_date='2021-06-11')
ardor = getdata('ardor', start_date='2018-05-03', end_date='2021-06-11')
ravencoin = getdata('ravencoin', start_date='2018-05-03', end_date='2021-06-11')

ardor <- ardor[ ,c("Date", "Close", "MarketCap")]
zcash <- zcash[ ,c("Date", "Close", "MarketCap")]
waves <- waves[ ,c("Date", "Close", "MarketCap")]
ravencoin <- ravencoin[ ,c("Date", "Close", "MarketCap")]

colnames(ardor) <- c("Date", "ardor_close", "ardor_cap")
colnames(zcash) <- c("Date", "zcash_close", "zcash_cap")
colnames(waves) <- c("Date", "waves_close", "waves_cap")
colnames(ravencoin) <- c("Date", "ravencoin_close", "ravencoin_cap")


ardor$Date <- as.Date(ardor$Date)
zcash$Date <- as.Date(zcash$Date)
waves$Date <- as.Date(waves$Date)
ravencoin$Date <- as.Date(ravencoin$Date)

base = merge(zcash, waves, by.x="Date", by.y="Date")
base = merge(base, ardor, by.x="Date", by.y="Date")
base = merge(base, ravencoin, by.x="Date", by.y="Date")
base = na.omit(base)

The start date is 5/18/2018 as full data exists for each cryptocurrency around this date. The next step is to calculate the cryptocurrency returns and create a portfolio in terms of their capitalization. 

# total 
base$tot_cap = base$zcash_cap + base$waves_cap + base$ardor_cap + base$ravencoin_cap
# percentage
base$perc_zcash = (base$zcash_cap/base$tot_cap)
base$perc_waves = (base$waves_cap/base$tot_cap)
base$perc_ardor = (base$ardor_cap/base$tot_cap)
base$perc_ravencoin = (base$ravencoin_cap/base$tot_cap)

#rates of return 
library(xts)
#for each currency
base$ret_zcash = diff.xts(log(base$zcash_close))
base$ret_waves = diff.xts(log(base$waves_close))
base$ret_ardor = diff.xts(log(base$ardor_close))
base$ret_ravencoin = diff.xts(log(base$ravencoin_close))

base$tot_ret = (base$ret_zcash*base$perc_zcash 
                + base$ret_waves*base$perc_waves
                + base$ret_ardor*base$perc_ardor
                + base$ret_ravencoin*base$perc_ravencoin)


base = na.omit(base)

In order to check whether there is an autocorrelation phenomenon in the portfolio returns, the graph of the autocorrelation function was analyzed.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
acf(base$tot_ret, lag.max = 49, na.action = na.pass,
    ylim = c(-0.2, 0.2), # we rescale the vertical axis
    col = "darkblue", lwd = 8,
    main = "ACF Chart of Portfolio Returns Squares")
acf(base$tot_ret^2, lag.max = 49, na.action = na.pass,
    ylim = c(-0.2, 0.2), # we rescale the vertical axis
    col = "darkblue", lwd = 8,
    main = "ACF Chart of Portfolio Returns Squares")

Delays 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 14, 15, 17 prove to be significant. Their problem of autocorrelation is in doubt. In the plot of the autocorrelation of the squares of returns, there are less significant lags, suggesting the occurrence of ARCH effects. In order to verify this hypothesis, formal LM tests were additionally carried out. 

ArchTest(base$tot_ret, lags = 5)

	ARCH LM-test; Null hypothesis: no ARCH effects

The test statistic of the ARCH LM test is 35.078 with its p-value almost 0, which can reject the null hypothesis that there are no ARCH effects in the portfolio. Based on the Durbin-Watson test, the null hypothesis of no autocorrelation for lags 1,2 and 4 can be rejected.

2. Sample split


Before estimating models, you need to split the dataset into in-sample and out-of-sample. The in-sample sample includes 954 observations from 04/05/2018 to 12/12/2020. The out-of-sample sample contains 179 observations from 2020-12-13 to 2021-06-10. The period in which the out-of-sample data is included was particularly turbulent, due to the "boom" that appeared on the cryptocurrency market at the turn of January / February 2021 and the sharp declines in May / June 2021, initiated, among others, by twitts Elon Musk. In-sample and out-of-smaple returns are shown below. 

insample = base[which(base$Date <= '2020-12-12'),]
outsample = base[which(base$Date >= '2020-12-13'),]

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(insample$Date, insample$tot_ret,
     type = 'l', lwd = 2, col = "green",
     main = 'In-sample wallet returns')
plot(outsample$Date, outsample$tot_ret,
     type = 'l', lwd = 2, col = "red",
     main = 'Out-of-sample wallet returns')

3. GARCH

The basic GARCH model that works well with most models is GARCH (1,1). The undoubted advantage of this model is the saving of parameters.

Below is an estimate of the GARCH (1,1) model via the "rugarch" package

spec_garch <- ugarchspec(mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0,0)),variance.model = list(model = 'sGARCH', garchOrder=c(1,1)))
garch <- ugarchfit(data = insample$tot_ret, spec = spec_garch)
garch

The omega, alpha and betha parameters are significant at the 5% level, while the problem with irrelevance is noticeable at the average (mu).

You can use the following techniques to deal with the problem above:

  • throwing it out
  • changing the model layout
  • changing p and q parameters for Garch
  • Include ARIMA effects

The use of other parameters in GARCH did not bring the desired results. In this case, it was decided to use a distribution other than the normal one. There is no need to throw out a variable right away if there is a possibility of improving this state, so it was decided to use a different distribution than normal - SGED (Skew Generalized Error Distribution) 

spec_garch_sged <- ugarchspec(mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0,0)),variance.model = list(model = 'sGARCH', garchOrder=c(1,1)),distribution.model=c('sged'))
garch_sged <- ugarchfit(data = insample$tot_ret, spec = spec_garch_sged)
garch_sged

After changing the distribution in the GARCH model, parameters that are not significant at the level of 5% no longer exist. The ARCH LM tests and the Ljung-Box test show no grounds for rejecting the null hypothesis of the lack of ARCH effects and the lack of autocorrelation. So the model explains the variance grouping and the autocorrelation.

The value of the Chi2 tet statistic is 8941.7 and its p-value is almost 0. The kurtosis is 12.37234 and the skewness is -1.486111 We can therefore assume that the model takes into account the phenomenon of grouping variance, but cannot cope with the leverage effect and the leptokurtosis effect

4. EGARCH

To eliminate the leverage effect, the EGARCH model, which is often used in modeling financial data, was used. The log of variance is modeled, resulting in a positive variance value regardless of the parameter values.

The EGARCH (1,1) model is described by the following equations: 

egarch_spec <- ugarchspec(mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0,0)),variance.model = list(model = 'eGARCH', garchOrder=c(1,1)))
egarch <- ugarchfit(data = insample$tot_ret, spec = egarch_spec)
egarch

In the EGARCH (1,1) model mu and alpha turned out to be irrelevant. In order to use a different method of improving the model, in this case a function was used that creates all compilations of models with the determined minimum and maximum values of p and q and sorting in terms of the AIC criterion. In this case, it was decided to set the values of p and q in the range 1-6. The table below shows the best criterion value for P = 3 and Q = 6.

7. Value at Risk

The "ugarchroll" function was used to estimate 1% of the value at risk. The Value at Risk computation starts with the first observation in the out-of-sample set. 

garch_f <- ugarchroll(spec_garch_sged, base$tot_ret, n.start=956,refit.every = 25, refit.window = "moving",VaR.alpha = 0.01)
egarch_f <- ugarchroll(egarch_spec_36, base$tot_ret, n.start=956,refit.every = 25, refit.window = "moving",VaR.alpha = 0.01)
csgarch_f <- ugarchroll(spec_csgarch55, base$tot_ret, n.start=956,refit.every = 25, refit.window = "moving",VaR.alpha = 0.01)

VaRGARCH <- garch_f@forecast$VaR[,1]
VaREGARCH <- egarch_f@forecast$VaR[,1]
VaRCGARCH <- csgarch_f@forecast$VaR[,1]

plot(outsample$tot_ret, type = "l",
     ylab = "Returns", main = "1% VaR", xaxt = "n", col=1,lwd=5)
lines(VaRGARCH, col = 2, lwd=5)
lines(VaREGARCH, col = 3,lwd=5)
lines(VaRCGARCH, col = 4,lwd=5 )

legend("bottomleft", 
  legend = c("Dane out-of-sample", "VaR Garch(1,1)", 'VaR EGARCH(3,6)', 'VaR CGARCH(1,1)x(5,0,5)'),

  pch = c(17,19), 
  bty = "n",

Value at Risk is the most stable for the sged-GARCH (1,1) model. There is too much hesitation with the EGARCH and CGARCH models.

8. Sensitivity Analysis

In order to test the sensitivity, how adopting the initial assumptions about the size of in-sample and out-of-sample influences the results of the model estimates and conclusions, it was decided to shorten the in-sample period starting from 2018-09-08, so that the out-of-sample -of-time was 365 days.

To check the sensitivity of the influence of in-sample and out-of-sample trials on model estimates and conclusions, the out-of-sample trial period has been extended, which this time starts from 2020-06-10 and has 365 observations, including thus shortening the in-sample by 186 observations 

insample2 = base[which(base$Date <= '2020-06-10'),]
outsample2 = base[which(base$Date >= '2020-06-11'),]

garch_f2 <- ugarchroll(spec_garch_sged, base$tot_ret, n.start=770,refit.every = 25, refit.window = "moving",VaR.alpha = 0.01)
egarch_f2 <- ugarchroll(egarch_spec_36, base$tot_ret, n.start=770,refit.every = 25, refit.window = "moving",VaR.alpha = 0.01)
csgarch_f2 <- ugarchroll(spec_csgarch55, base$tot_ret, n.start=770,refit.every = 25, refit.window = "moving",VaR.alpha = 0.01)

Conclusions

The collaboration was created as a cryptocurrency portfolio consisting of Ardor, Wave, RavenCoin and Zcash as a portfolio weighted by market capitalization. ZCash had the largest share in the portfolio. Three models from the GARCH family were analyzed, improving the models from various techniques: parameter changes, AR and MA equality, and model distribution. The best improvement in improving the model turned out to be the change in distribution with the normal GED distribution. Not only from the best values in the criteria, but also to have the most stable estimates. Risk values that have fluctuation rates support the initial trials as well as in the quality assessment, which is the extension of the window beyond the sample.

It is worth the currency that market modeling is not the simplest data day, to obtain non-cryptocurrency data as long as they have great fluctuations, or the securities. The cryptocurrency market is too unpredictable for price predictions, but you can enter Elon Musk's recent entries on twitter, after which the cryptocurrency opinions about bitcoin were too low due to its decline, resulting in other ovals. An important fact is also the turbulent period of the last year on the cryptocurrency market. In March 2020, when the lockdown was announced by COVID, cryptocurrency prices improved. I attended at the end of January 2021 the so-called "altcoin season" after the earlier change in bitcoin growth, when prices are also introduced, the cryptocurrency began to rise.
